        <h2 class="font-montserrat font-bold text-2xl md:text-3xl text-[#1e3a5f] mb-6">How No Deposit Car Loans Work</h2>
        <p class="text-gray-700 font-lato font-light leading-relaxed mb-4">A no deposit car loan is vehicle finance where the lender provides 100% of the purchase price. Instead of paying a portion upfront, you borrow the entire amount and repay over the loan term (typically 1–7 years) with interest. Most no deposit car loans are secured, meaning the vehicle itself acts as collateral.</p>
        <p class="text-gray-700 font-lato font-light leading-relaxed mb-4">When you apply, the lender assesses your ability to afford the full repayment amount. Because you are not reducing the loan with a deposit, your regular repayments will be higher. The lender looks at your income (after tax), existing financial commitments, living expenses, employment history, credit score, and the vehicle being purchased.</p>
        <p class="text-gray-700 font-lato font-light leading-relaxed mb-4">Some lenders also allow you to include on-road costs — registration, stamp duty, comprehensive insurance, and dealer delivery fees — in the loan amount. This means you could drive away with absolutely zero upfront costs, though you will be borrowing more than the car's value.</p>
      </section>
      <section class="mb-16">
