        <p class="text-gray-700 font-lato font-light leading-relaxed mb-4">Many lenders offer the same advertised interest rate regardless of whether a deposit is paid. The difference is in total cost because you borrow a larger amount.</p>
        <div class="bg-[#0d4d3e]/5 border-l-4 border-[#10b981] rounded-r-lg p-6 my-6"><p class="text-[#0d4d3e] font-lato font-light leading-relaxed">Example on a $35,000 car at 7% p.a. over 5 years: No deposit = ~$693/month, $6,580 total interest. With 10% deposit ($3,500 down) = ~$624/month, $5,920 interest — saving $69/month and $660 total. With 20% deposit ($7,000 down) = ~$554/month, $5,260 interest — saving $139/month and $1,320 total.</p></div>
        <p class="text-gray-700 font-lato font-light leading-relaxed mb-4">While a deposit saves money overall, if you need a car now and do not have savings available, a no deposit loan gets you mobile immediately. You can always make extra repayments later to reduce your balance faster.</p>
      </section>
