        <p class="text-gray-700 font-lato font-light leading-relaxed mb-4">Eligibility generally requires a reasonable credit history (though specialist lenders can help with impaired credit), stable employment or regular income, and the ability to demonstrate you can comfortably afford the repayments. For borrowers with excellent credit, approval with no deposit is typically straightforward.</p>
      </section>
      <section class="mb-16">
        <h2 class="font-montserrat font-bold text-2xl md:text-3xl text-[#1e3a5f] mb-6">Benefits and Risks of No Deposit Car Finance</h2>
        <p class="text-gray-700 font-lato font-light leading-relaxed mb-4">The main benefit is obvious — you can get a car now without needing to save for months or years. This is valuable if you need a vehicle urgently for a new job, family needs, or because your current car has broken down. It also preserves cash for other expenses like insurance, registration, or an emergency fund.</p>
        <p class="text-gray-700 font-lato font-light leading-relaxed mb-4">The main risk is negative equity. New cars depreciate 15–20% in the first year. If you finance 100% with no deposit, you may owe more than the car is worth for the first one to three years. If you need to sell during this period, sale proceeds may not cover the outstanding balance. Mitigate this by choosing a car that holds its value, making extra repayments, and opting for a shorter loan term.</p>
      </section>
